One of the smaller bourgeois growths of the Medoc that Chateau-bottles its own wine. Good character, light, pleasant.

Warm, generous, round, the kind of wine that is pleasing while still relatively young.

A true discovery. Of a grand Pomerol class. Excellent depth and much longevity. Worth much more.

This excellent light red wine is not Chateau-bottled. It is a selection of Baron Philippe de Rothschild and it proudly bears his name. This is the last of the 1962 in America and in France. Get it while still available.

439 CHATEAU GAFFELIERE-NAUDES Site 3.59 38.75

Many wine authorities believe that this vineyard is surpassed in St. Emilion only by Chateau Cheval Blanc. Outstanding.

414 CHATEAU LA LAGUNE

(Ludon-Medoc) 3.65 39.85 This 1962 La Lagune is now the rage of Bordeaux. It is the proud property of Mr. Chayoux, who has done much in recent years to make it one of the oustanding vineyards of the Medoc. Because of a relatively high ratio of merlot grapes, it is one of the most mature of the 1962 Clarets. Light, and excellent.

A unique Claret. Much heavier, darker, and deeper in flavor than its neighbors. A smaller version of either Chateau Mouton Rothschild or Chateau Latour—similar in style.

431 CHATEAU CANTEMERLE (Macaiu-Menec) ..... 6s. 5263. 3.99 43.10

Admirable balance and bouquet. Similar in character to the finer red wines of the Graves district such as Pape Clement and Bouscaut.

We again quote from the Vintage Chart that appears in the newly published book “Wines and Spirits’.

“1962—quietly, and with a minimum of publicity, the neglected 1962 Clarets have finally won deserved recognition among the world’s wine-lovers. In their own way, they have some- thing to offer us. Uniformly, they are excellent, early-matur- ing, soft, fruity, a fine bouquet and can be enjoyed for present drinking. Undoubtedly, the best Claret values available today.”

No. Bottle Case 449 CHATEAU MONTROSE (St. Estephe) 3.99 43.10

A great 2nd Growth, 1855 Medoc classification. A slow-to-mature wine which reached height of quality in 1962. Similar in characteristics to Chateau Latour. A favorite in England.

708 CHATEAU LEOVILLE LASCASES (et Julien) =. 3.99 43.10

One of our favorite Clarets—particularly since 1959 when Dr. Peynaud, head of the Wine Department of the University of Bordeaux, directed the production.

103 CHATEAU LASCOMBES (Margaux) . 3.99 43.10 Alexis Lichine is proud of the wine that he produced here in 1962. The world must have recognized this because it is among the most difficult of all Clarets to obtain. Great finesse with a bouquet that is described as ‘reminiscent of violets’.

420 CHATEAU COS D’ESTOURNEL [st Esteone) o.oo 4.29 46.35

Like Chateau Montrose above, this Estephe is hard and slow to develop in a concentrated year such as 1961. However, in 1962, a superb balance was achieved.

This great Graves is in the ‘Grand Class’. It is no ordinary event to be able to obtain such stature, breed and harmony for $6.19.

619 CHATEAU AUSONE (St. Emilion)... 7.99 86.30 We wanted you to taste a great First Growth from an outstanding year below $10.00 per bottle. We, therefore, priced this excellent Ausone down to a workable level. You will like it.

147 CHATEAU PETRUS (Pomerol) ...... 9.95 107.45 Achieves more pronounced velvetiness and fruit than any other Claret whether produced in Medoc, Graves or St. Emilion. Because there are only 16 acres in total, it is the most difficult of all of the 1st Growths to obtain. A rarity. Truly magnificent.

(Paula) 6 9.95 107.45 Small production—full-bodied—fleshy—rich. The biggest of all of the wines

of the Medoc—long-lasting and the proud property of the Baron Philippe de Rothschild.

213 CHATEAU LATOUR (Pauillac) ..... 9.95 107.45

About 85% of Chateau Latour is planted with the Cabernet Sauvignon grape. This partially accounts for its bigness, deep color, slow matura- tion and long-life. Even its 1870 is still good today.

115 CHATEAU LAFITE ROTHSCHILD

(Pauillac) 9.95 107.45 In 1858, Baron James de Rothschild bought Lafite for five million francs. It is a pride of the Rothschild family and the present Baron Eli spares no expense in seeing that the quality, disinction and elegance of the Lafite wines are maintained.

162 CHATEAU HAUT BRION (Graves) .. 9.95 107.45

Owned by the Clarence Dillon family, Chateau Haut Brion has achieved a supreme position under the loving care of its director, Seymour Weller. Great power combines with unique subtlety here.
